Dismissing the opinions or needs of people with disabilities in policy-making decisions is unethical, unlawful, and contrary to principles of equity and human rights. The United Nations Convention on the Rights of Persons with Disabilities (CRPD) explicitly mandates the inclusion of disabled individuals in decisions affecting their lives, emphasizing their right to participation, accessibility, and non-discrimination. Excluding their voices perpetuates systemic inequities, undermines the validity of policies, and violates legal frameworks designed to protect marginalized groups. Ethical governance requires centering diverse perspectives to ensure policies are inclusive, effective, and reflective of societal values.

